### 2024/01/04 - v1.2.0 🚨

Mandatory for Validators & Miners

The update is **LIVE**.

__Because of the nature of this update, from now on if validators not up to date, will be blacklisted for a static period.__

If any issue observed until then you will be prevented.

Following changes:
- Common: Update proof of work algorithm in favor of an asics-resistant.
- Common: Increase timeout to 60 seconds.
- Common: Increased a little bit the difficulty.
- Common: Decreased drastically calls from validators.
- Common: Adjust scoring system for the time elapsed.
- Common: Revamp completely parser arguments, check readme for more details.
- Common: Improved global architecture of the repository. 
- Common: Update gitignore to have less chance of untracked files issue.
- Miners: Add the validator version verification. 
- Validators: script entirely refactored in favor of a Validator class.
- Validators: Pre-add code base for miner version verification.

```sh
git pull

pm2 restart <id>

```

**NetUID 27 Post-Mortem: Analysis & Solution** 💻 :bts: 

Compute Subnet faced challenges in its initial approach to validating miner hardware capabilities. Here is a post-mortem analysis that shows the issues faced & the solutions implemented to create a more secure & reliable subnetwork.

**Initial Challenges:** The original miner validation involved a script on miners' machines, encrypted by validators. Miners found a way to exploit binary files and deceive the Linux kernel to manipulate script outcomes, faking hardware capabilities such as multiple GPUs or extensive RAM.

This major loophole in the Python-based script system led to fraudulent activities, allowing for the scoring system to be cheated. This manipulation undermined the integrity of the system and forced us to halt emissions.

**Solution Implementation:** In response to these vulnerabilities, our blockchain team quickly adopted a proof-of-work approach similar to that of Bitcoin.

Miners must now find specific hashes to demonstrate real computational power, preventing fraud. This approach uses a brute force password + salt with BLAKE2b-512 algorithm (which is ASICS resistant) for each miner to prevent reuse of previous hashes. Miners validate their hardware by cracking these hashes.

The new system has shown promising results, accurately measuring each miner's hardware capability, ensuring fairness and deterring fraudulent activities. This shift marks a significant step in building a resilient, permission-less compute network. Our goal is to continue evolving and strengthening the ecosystem in collaboration with validators.

Our team’s dedication to creating a secure compute subnet — a critical component of decentralized AI — has led to an increase in emissions and a call for continued support from the community. 

Read the full Post-Mortem breakdown here: https://medium.com/@neuralinternet/netuid-27-post-mortem-4ed708041bc6
